'''Fascin''' is an [[actin]] cross-linking [[protein]].

It is a 54-58&nbsp;[[kilodalton]] monomeric [[actin]] filament bundling protein originally isolated from [[sea urchin]] egg but also found in ''[[Drosophila]]''<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.90.19.9115 |last=Bryan |first=Joseph |author2=Robert A. Edwards |author3=P Matsudaira |author4=J Otto |author5=J Wulfkuhle  |date=October 1993 |title=Fascin, an echinoid actin-bundling protein, is a homolog of the Drosophila singed gene product |journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America]] |volume=90 |issue=19 |pages=9115<U+2013>9119 |issn=0027-8424 |pmid=8415664 |pmc=47512 }}</ref> and vertebrates,<ref>{{cite journal |last=Edwards |first=Robert A. |author2=Joseph Bryan |year=1995 |title=Fascins, a family of actin bundling proteins |journal=[[Cell Motility and the Cytoskeleton]] |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |volume=32 |issue=1 |pages=1<U+2013>9 |issn=0886-1544 |doi=10.1002/cm.970320102 |pmid=8674129 }}</ref> including humans.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Yamashiro-Matsumura |first=S. |author2=F. Matsumura |date=April 1985 |title=Purification and characterization of an F-actin-bundling 55-kilodalton protein from HeLa cells |journal=[[Journal of Biological Chemistry]] |volume=260 |issue=8 |pages=5087<U+2013>5097 |issn=0021-9258 |pmid=3886649 }}</ref> Fascin (from the Latin for ''bundle'') is spaced at 11&nbsp;nanometre intervals along the [[Protein filament|filament]]. The bundles in cross section are seen to be hexagonally packed, and the longitudinal spacing is compatible with a model where fascin [[cross-link]]s at alternating 4 and 5 actins.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0022-2836(78)90345-5 |last=Bryan |first=Joseph |author2=R. E. Kane |date=October 1978 |title=Separation and interaction of the major components of sea urchin actin gel |journal=[[Journal of Molecular Biology]] |volume=125 |issue=2 |pages=207<U+2013>224 |issn=0022-2836 |pmid=731692 }}</ref>  It is calcium insensitive and [[monomer]]ic.

Fascin binds [[beta-catenin]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1083/jcb.134.5.1271 |last=Tao |first=Y. S. |coauthors=R. A. Edwards, B. Tubb, S. Wang, Joseph Bryan and P. D. McCrea |date=September 1996 |title=beta-Catenin associates with the actin-bundling protein fascin in a noncadherin complex |journal=Journal of Cell Biology |publisher=[[Rockefeller University Press]] |volume=134 |issue=5 |pages=1271<U+2013>1281 |issn=0021-9525 |pmid=8794867 |pmc=2120989 }}</ref> and colocalizes with it at the leading edges and borders of [[epithelial]] and [[endothelial]] cells. The role of Fascin in regulating [[cytoskeletal]] structures for the maintenance of [[cell adhesion]], coordinating [[motility]] and [[cellular infiltration|invasion]] through interactions with [[signalling pathway]]s is an active area of research especially from the [[cancer]] biology perspective.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Adams |first=Josephine C. |date=October 2004 |title=Roles of fascin in cell adhesion and motility |journal=[[Current Opinion in Cell Biology]] |publisher= |volume=16 |issue=5 |pages=590<U+2013>596 |issn=0955-0674 |pmid= 15363811|pmc= |doi=10.1016/j.ceb.2004.07.009 |bibcode= |oclc= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Hashimoto |first=Yosuke |author2=Marek Skacel |author3=Josephine C. Adams  |date=September 2005 |title=Roles of fascin in human carcinoma motility and signaling: Prospects for a novel biomarker? |journal=The International Journal of Biochemistry & Cell Biology |publisher=[[Elsevier]] |volume=37 |issue=9 |pages=1787<U+2013>1804 |issn=1357-2725 |doi=10.1016/j.biocel.2005.05.004 |pmid=16002322 }}</ref> Fascin localizes to actin-rich protrusions at the cell surface called filopodia. Recent study shows that fascin also localizes to invadopodia, membrane protrusions formed at the adherent cell surface that facilitate extracellular matrix (ECM) invasion, this provide a potential molecular mechanism for how fascin increases the invasiveness of cancer cells since fascin expression is upregulated in a spectrum of cancers.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Li A, Dawson JC, Forero-Vargas M, Spence HJ, Yu X, K<U+00F6>nig I, Anderson K,  Machesky LM | title = The actin-bundling protein fascin stabilizes actin in invadopodia  and potentiates protrusive invasion | journal = Curr. Biol. | volume = 20 | issue = 4 | pages = 339<U+2013>45 |date=Feb 2010 | doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2009.12.035| url = | issn = }}</ref>

Abnormal fascin [[protein expression|expression]] or function has been implicated in [[breast cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Grothey |first=Axel |author2=R. Hashizume |author3=A. A. Sahin |author4=P. D. McCrea  |year=2000 |title=Fascin, an actin-bundling protein associated with cell motility, is upregulated in hormone receptor negative breast cancer |journal=[[British Journal of Cancer]] |volume=83 |issue= 7|pages=870<U+2013>873 |issn=0007-0920 |doi=10.1054/bjoc.2000.1395 |pmid=10970687 |pmc=2374674 }}</ref> [[colon cancer]],<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0002-9440(10)63799-6 |last=Jawhari |first=Aida U. |author2=Andrea Buda |author3=Michelle Jenkins |author4=Khurram Shehzad |author5=Catherine Sarraf |author6=Masao Noda |author7=Michael J. G. Farthing |author8=Massimo Pignatelli |author9=Josephine C. Adams  |displayauthors=9 |date=January 2003 |title=Fascin, an actin-bundling protein, modulates colonic epithelial cell invasiveness and differentiation in vitro |journal=American Journal of Pathology |publisher=American Society for Investigative Pathology |volume=162 |issue=1 |pages=69<U+2013>80 |issn=0002-9440 |pmid=12507891 |pmc=1851132 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Vignjevic |first=Danijela |coauthors=Marie Schoumacher, Nancy Gavert, Klaus-Peter Janssen, Gloria Jih, Marick La<U+00E9>, Daniel Louvard, Avri Ben-Ze'ev, Sylvie Robine |date=July 2007 |title=Fascin, a Novel Target of <U+00DF>-Catenin-TCF Signaling, Is Expressed at the Invasive Front of Human Colon Cancer |journal=[[Cancer Research (journal)|Cancer Research]] |volume=67 |issue=14 |pages=6844<U+2013>6853 |issn=0008-5472 |pmid=17638895 |doi=10.1158/0008-5472.CAN-07-0929 }}</ref> esophageal [[squamous cell carcinoma]],<ref>{{cite journal |last=Hashimoto |first=Yosuke |author2=Tetsuo Ito |author3=Harutaka Inoue |author4=Tomoyuki Okumura |author5=Eiji Tanaka |author6=Shigeru Tsunoda |author7=Motoshige Higashiyama |author8=Go Watanabe |author9=Masayuki Imamura |author10=Yutaka Shimada  |date=April 2005 |title=Prognostic Significance of Fascin Overexpression in Human Esophageal Squamous Cell Carcinoma |journal=Clinical Cancer Research |publisher=[[American Association for Cancer Research]] |volume=11 |issue=7 |pages=2597<U+2013>2605 |issn=1078-0432 |pmid=15814639 |doi=10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-04-1378 }}</ref> [[gallbladder cancer]]<ref>{{cite journal |last=Roh |first=Y. H. |author2=Y. H. Kim |author3=H. J. Choi |author4=K. E. Lee |author5=M. S. Roh  |date=March 2009 |title=Fascin overexpression correlates with positive thrombospondin-1 and syndecan-1 expressions and a more aggressive clinical course in patients with gallbladder cancer |journal=Journal of Hepatobiliary Pancreatic Surgery |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer International]] |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=315<U+2013>21 |issn=0944-1166 |pmid=19259612 |doi=10.1007/s00534-009-0046-1 }}</ref> and [[prostate cancer]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Darnel |first=Andrew D. |author2=Emy Behmoaram |author3=Robin T. Vollmer |author4=Jacques Corcos |author5=Krikor Bijian1 |author6=Kanishka Sircar |author7=Jie Su |author8=Jinsong Jiao |author9=Moulay A. Alaoui-Jamali |author10=Tarek A. Bismar  |date=February 2009 |title=Fascin regulates prostate cancer cell invasion and is associated with metastasis and biochemical failure in prostate cancer |journal=Clinical Cancer Research |publisher=[[American Association for Cancer Research]] |volume=15 |issue=4 |pages=1376<U+2013>1383 |issn=1078-0432 |pmid=19228738 |doi=10.1158/1078-0432.CCR-08-1789 }}</ref> It is also helpful in identifying Hodgkin cells.

==Structure==
Fascin is a structural protein found in mesenchyme, nervous, and retinal tissue and is used in the bundling of [[actin]] molecules.<ref name="pmid20601080">{{cite journal | author = Jayo A, Parsons M | title = Fascin: a key regulator of cytoskeletal dynamics | journal = Int. J. Biochem. Cell Biol. | volume = 42 | issue = 10 | pages = 1614<U+2013>7 |date=October 2010 | pmid = 20601080 | doi = 10.1016/j.biocel.2010.06.019 | url = | issn = }}</ref>

The structure of human fascin has been determined to a resolution of 2.9 <U+00C5> and reveals an arrangement of four tandem [[beta-trefoil domain]]s that form a two lobed structure with pseudo 2-fold symmetry. It is stabilized by a [[hydrophobe|hydrophobic]] core and a [[hydrophile|hydrophilic]] surface since it is often found inside cell [[cytoplasm]] in the formation of [[filopodia]].<ref name="pmid20434460"/>

